@Mike

Not this again. You may have your own rules for what you consider a streak, but why do you care how others define their streaks? Let everybody enjoy these puzzles in their own, preferred way, and stop raining on their parade.

Also, I will never understand how remembering random trivia is somehow better than looking it up. Knowing a name, brand or title is no test of wit or language ability. If I constructed a puzzle consisting only of trivia I personally know, and you failed to solve it, would you consider that proof of your inadequate crossword skills?

@Barry Ancona

I know. Still, if you don't know it, you have a harder time than if you do. Knowing it is not a skill, and often is pretty worthless. What do I care what some brand is called? 

Of course, and this relates to what @Jim wrote, too, as a non-native speaker of English I need crosses to a greater extent than either of you do, which influences my position on this.

@Mike

I never include a puzzle for which I've looked up an answer as part of a streak.

Where I have problems is with multiple attempts after getting the "Close" screen.  I sometimes include that in the streak, but once I recall too many of them, I begin to feel like it's a fake streak. So, I voluntarily give up the streak by hitting "Check Puzzle".

