@Alexis
I actually share the name a a fairly famous person, and she'll occasionally show up in the puzzle. I'm always unreasonably excited.

That said, there are about fifteen billion Katies, Kathys, Kates, and Katherines out there, and it gets a little tiresome. There were three of us in my grade in high school, out of a class of 60.

@Katie

I teach at university. You wouldn't believe how common the name Julia is among 18-23 year olds over here. In some classes (ca. 30 people) there are 3 or more Julias. It's so popular in fact that Julka - the Polish diminutive for Julia - has recently become a slangy term for a teenage girl.

In my school days 30 years ago Katarzyna (Katherine) was nearly as common though.

@Katie

Yes it’s quite handy that in most places (work, sports clubs etc), I’m the only Alexis and so can pretty much just go by first name

That said, all through school I was one of several ‘Alex’s (up to 2 or 3 in a class of thirty, and between 2 and 7 classes per grade). Invariably I was the only Alexis in a sea of Alexandras and Alexanders though, which meant at least I could just insist that folks not shorten my name — otherwise I probably _would_ have ended up as an Alex!

@Andy G
My average Sunday time is the highest because that's the one I tend to savor and take my time with (it's also the biggest).

Sat is the next longest because I find them very difficult (usually) but there is only 5 min difference between my average Fri and average Sat times. Thursday's average is right in the middle of them, so they are fairly close.

@Andy G

For me, solve times increase as the week progresses, and this includes Thursdays (average solve time just under 24 minutes), Fridays (under 26 minutes) and Saturdays (slightly under 29 minutes).

The biggest increase in average solve time for me is between Wednesday and Thursday - almost 6 minutes. I'm ignoring Sundays here, as the larger grid size means any direct comparison is impossible.

